<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> ND3 gives you 10% more HPs while CS3 reduces melee damage by 10%. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Bzzzt. Incorrect. Thank you for playing. You win a year's supply of rice-a-roni, the San Francisco Treat(tm). <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
CS does not reduce melee damage by 10%. The description says:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Each skill level gives the character an increased ability to reduce the damage he takes in combat (damage mitigation). The first skill level increases the character's damage mitigation by 2%, the second skill level raises the damage mitigation increase to 5% and the third raises the increase to 10%.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
That doesn't say it reduces damage. It says it increases damage mitigation by that factor. That is not the same thing. <br>
<br>
It's generally said that there are two components to AC - damage avoidance (did you get hit or not) and damage mitigation (how much damage did you take once you are hit).<br>
<br>
CS seems to add to the mitigation effects. It will not reduce damage by a flat percentage but what it (hopefully) does is mean that you will generally get hit for less damage than you would have without it, over all. If a mob hits for 120 max, it will still hit you for 120, but hopefully not as often.<br>
<br>
This is why it's hard to quantify the benefits of this skill. Tough one to parse.<br>
<br>
